<P>The projector and his a&s;&s;ociate having obtained
the promi&s;e of the publi&s;her, that this intimation
&s;hould appear next day, went early in the morn|ing
to a public hou&s;e, and occupying a room,
the windows of which fronted the ho&s;ier's door,
&s;at with joyful expectation to &s;ee the effect of
their &s;cheme, which &s;oon yielded them all the &s;a|tisfaction
they could de&s;ire. The &s;hop was no
&s;ooner opened, than it was &s;urrounded by a great
number of the Cannaille, who having heard the
adverti&s;ement read in ale-hou&s;es, came (each with
a cat under his arm) in hopes of making an ad|vantageous
bargain; for though many of them
were too incon&s;iderable to produce &s;uch an ani|mal
of their own property, they had made free
with the fir&s;t cats they could pick up, and every
one repair$d with all po&s;&s;ible di&s;patch to the ap|pointed
place, with a view of fore&s;ta$$ing the
