among a &s;et of young noblemen, who had
denounced war again&s;t temperance, oeconomy,
and common &s;en&s;e, and were indeed the devoted
&s;ons of tumult, wa&s;te, and prodigality. Not
that Peregr$$e reli&s;hed tho&s;e &s;cenes, which were
a &s;ucce&s;&s;ion of ab&s;urd extravagance, devoid of a$$
true &s;pirit, ta&s;te, or enjoyment: but his vanity
prompted him to mingle with tho&s;e who were
intitled the choice &s;pirits of the age; and his di&s;|po&s;ition
was &s;o pliable, as to ad$pt it&s;elf ea&s;ily to
<PB N="204" REF="307">
the mea&s;ures of his company, where he had not
